      "\n        <;>\n        (try cases ns <;> simp_all (config := {decide := true})) <;>\n        (try {\n          simp_all [List.reverse_cons, List.reverse_nil, List.append_assoc, List.append_nil, List.append_eq_append_iff]\n          <;>\n          aesop\n        }) <;>\n        (try {\n          simp_all [List.reverse_cons, List.reverse_nil, List.append_assoc, List.append_nil, List.append_eq_append_iff]\n          <;>\n          aesop\n        })",
      "\n   - We need to prove that `as.init = as.tail.reverse`.\n\n   But this is not necessarily true unless `as` is very specific. Hmm, perhaps this suggests that my previous assumption about `q.reverse.tailSL` when `bs = []` was wrong.\n\n   Actually, perhaps `q.reverse.tailSL` when `q = ⟨as, [], ok⟩` is not `⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩`, but depends on `as`:\n   - For `q = ⟨[], [], ok⟩`, then `q.reverse = ⟨[], [], ...⟩`, and `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], [], ...⟩` (because `as = []` and `bs = []`). But `q = ⟨[], [], ok⟩`, and `List.init q.fromSL = []`, while `q.init.fromSL = []`, so this works.\n   - For `q = ⟨[x], [], ok⟩`, then `q.reverse = ⟨[], [x], ...⟩`. `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], []⟩` because `q.reverse = ⟨[], [x], ...⟩`, so `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[x].tail, [], ...⟩ = ⟨[], [], ...⟩` (because `[x].tail = []`). So `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], [], ...⟩`, `(q.reverse.tailSL).fromSL = []`, and `(q.reverse.tailSL).fromSL.reverse = []`. Meanwhile, `q.fromSL = [x]`, `List.init [x] = []`, so we have equality.\n\n   Hmm, so perhaps it actually is `⟨[], as.tail⟩` if `as ≠ []`, but not quite?\n\nWait, no. Actually, `q.reverse = ⟨bs, as, ...⟩`. So if `q = ⟨as, [], ok⟩`, then `q.reverse = ⟨[], as, ...⟩`.\n\nNow, `q.reverse.tailSL`:\n- If `bs = []`, i.e., `q.reverse = ⟨[], as, ...⟩`, then `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨as.tail, [], ...⟩` if `as ≠ []`, or `⟨[], [], ...⟩` if `as = []`.\n\nWait, no: The definition of `tailSL` for `⟨as, bs, ...⟩` is:\n- If `as = []`, then it's `⟨[], bs.tail, ...⟩`, else it's `⟨as.tail, bs, ...⟩`.\n\nSo if we have `q.reverse = ⟨[], as, ...⟩`, then `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩` (because `as' = []`, and `bs' = as`, so we take `⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩`).\n\nThus, if `q = ⟨as, [], ...⟩`, then `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩`.\n\nThen `(q.reverse.tailSL).fromSL = [] ++ as.tail = as.tail`.\n\nThus `(q.reverse.tailSL).fromSL.reverse = as.tail.reverse`, and we need to prove that `List.init (as ++ []) = as.tail.reverse`, i.e., `as.init = as.tail.reverse`.\n\nBut for `as = [a, b, c]`, `as.init = [a, b]`, and `as.tail = [b, c]`, `as.tail.reverse = [c, b]`, so not equal. So this is false.\n\nBut `q.init.fromSL` should be `as.init`, because:\n`q.init = q.reverse.tailSL.reverse = ⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩.reverse = ⟨as.tail, [], ...⟩`, and thus `q.init.fromSL = as.tail ++ [] = as.tail`.\n\nBut earlier, I thought `q.init = ⟨as, [], ...⟩.reverse.tailSL.reverse = ⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩.reverse = ⟨as.tail, [], ...⟩`, so `q.init.fromSL = as.tail`.\n\nBut in Lean, we have for `q = ⟨as, [], ...⟩`, `q.reverse = ⟨[], as, ...⟩`, `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], as.tail, ...⟩`, so `q.init = ⟨as.tail, [], ...⟩`, and `q.init.fromSL = as.tail` (since `as.tail ++ [] = as.tail`).\n\nBut `List.init (as ++ []) = as.init`, and we're trying to prove `as.init = as.tail`, which is not true unless `as` is very special.\n\nBut in Lean, the actual theorem to prove is: For `q = ⟨as, bs, ...⟩`, `List.init q.fromSL = q.init.fromSL`. For `q = ⟨[a, b, c], [], ...⟩`, `q.fromSL = [a, b, c]`, `List.init q.fromSL = [a, b]`, and `q.init.fromSL = [b, c]`? No, because `q.reverse = ⟨[], [a, b, c], ...⟩`, `q.reverse.tailSL = ⟨[], [a, b, c].tail⟩ = ⟨[], [b, c]⟩`, `q.init = ⟨[b, c], [], ...⟩`, `q.init.fromSL = [b, c] ++ [] = [b, c]`.\n\nBut `List.init q.fromSL = [a, b]`, and `[a, b] ≠ [b, c]`. \n\nThis suggests that perhaps the theorem is false, but this contradicts the example given in the Lean code, where for `[1,2,3]`, `init` was `[1,2]`, which is correct.\n\nBut in Lean, `[1,2,3]` is represented as `⟨[1,2], [3], ...⟩`, not `⟨[1,2,3], [], ...⟩`.\n\nAh! The problem is that `⟨[a, b, c], [], ...⟩` is not a valid symmetric list because the lengths of `[a,b,c]` and `[]` differ by more than one.",
      "hs.reverse",
